Based on the reviewed literature, bite-wing radiographs remain the gold standard for diagnosing posterior interproximal caries in children. The evidence supports that these radiographs, particularly those employing the bisecting angle technique, allow for highly accurate visualization of these difficult-to-detect lesions. While other modalities like digital lateral cephalograms can aid in certain scenarios, they do not match the specificity and ease-of-use of targeted bite-wing films. Thus, my position remains aligned with Option A: Bite wing with Bisecting Angle technique. \boxed{A}
